  "prompt": "What are proportional taxes?",
  "response": "Proportional taxes, also known as flat taxes, are a type of tax system in which the tax rate remains constant regardless of the amount of income or wealth that is earned. In other words, everyone pays the same percentage of their income in taxes, regardless of whether they earn a little or a lot. \n\nFor example, under a proportional tax system, if the tax rate is set at 15%, an individual earning $30,000 a year would pay $4,500 in taxes, while someone earning $100,000 would pay $15,000. The tax burden is distributed equally in terms of percentage, but not in absolute terms, meaning that lower-income individuals generally pay a smaller amount in total taxes compared to higher-income earners.\n\nProponents of proportional taxes argue that they are simpler and fairer because everyone pays the same rate. Critics, on the other hand, argue that they can be regressive, as lower-income individuals may find a flat percentage of their income to be a more significant burden compared to wealthier individuals.",
